  "subject": "Empirical signal: PO hit cross-machine skill deployment friction 2026-05-24 (asked how to install /oagp-onboard on a new machine); current 'clone Thingalog + mklink junction' workflow works but is lossy; suggests plugin-packaging strategic call (hand-off §3.D) should move up your queue",

  "sent": "2026-05-24T09:05:00-04:00",
  "action_required": false,

  "body": "Empirical signal from PO 2026-05-24 worth surfacing to your seat. PO asked orgdef-strategist (this session) how to install /oagp-onboard on a new machine. The operational answer is straightforward — clone Thingalog repo, create mklink /J junction from %USERPROFILE%\\.claude\\skills\\oagp-onboard to <thingalog>/skills/oagp-onboard, restart Claude Code — but that workflow has four real friction points: (1) requires Thingalog repo access (portfolio-private); (2) requires user knowledge of the canonical-by-reference framing (you find the canonical-content via reading hand-off memos); (3) junction-pinning means the new machine's skill is git-pinned to whatever SHA Thingalog is at when cloned (no auto-update); (4) doesn't compose with oagp-org/skills/ (currently empty pending your re-homing call). The friction is exactly what hand-off §3.D (OAGP plugin packaging strategic call) and §3.E (cross-runtime delivery package coordination) are meant to solve. PO hitting this friction in normal use is the most reliable empirical signal that plugin-packaging priority should move up. action_required false because this is signal, not action-required by your seat — you triage when you take up the plugin-packaging item. Body has more detail on the friction taxonomy and the operational workaround currently in use.",
  "body_ref": "2026-05-24-0905--orgdef-strategist--oagp-strategist--cross-machine-skill-deployment-friction-empirical-signal.body.md",

